London seat at the [[1727 British general election|1727 general election]].. In 1732 he became Deputy Governor of the Royal Exchange Aassurance Corporation.<ref name = HOP2>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/lockwood-richard-1676-1756 | title= LOCKWOOD, Richard (1676-1756), of College Hill, London, and Dews Hall, nr. Maldon, Essex.| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1715-1754)| accessdate = 18 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nLockwood was returned as MP for Worcester after a contest at the  [[1734 British general election|1734 general election]] and sat  again as a Tory in the 1734 Parliament. In 1735 he bought the estate of Dews Hall in Essex.<ref name=BHO>{{cite book |url =   http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/essex/vol4/pp76-81  |pages= 76\u201381 |title= 'Lambourne: Manors', in A History of the County of Essex: Volume 4, Ongar Hundred,,|author= W R Powell |publisher = British History | date= 1956|accessdate =  27 December  2018}}</ref> He  spoke on the gin bill in 1736,  voted against the Government on the Spanish convention in 1739 and the place bill in 1740, and opposed a bill concerned with frauds in marine insurance on 27 March 1740. He did not seek re-election at the [[1741 British general election|1741 general election]] <ref name=HOP2/> and retired to Dews Hall. He enlarged and refronted the old brick building  in the classical style.<ref name=BHO/>\n\nLockwood died on 30 August1756, aged 80.<ref name=HOP2/> Dews Hall descended to his eldest son Richard.<ref name=BHO/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Henry Lee Warner]]\n | before2 = [[Edmund Lambert]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Hindon (UK Parliament constituency)|Hindon]]\n | years =   [[1713 British general election|1713]]\u2013[[1715 British general election|1715]]\n | with  =  [[Reynolds Calthorpe (1689-1714)|Reynolds Calthorpe, the younger]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[